Review:
I have never purchased a George Foreman grill; the infomercials alone were enough to scare me off. When I moved into my apartment a few months back, I realized that my roommate, the consummate college student, had a George Foreman Next Generation grill that he never used, and I figured it was worth a shot. Maybe the former boxing champ slapped his name on something pretty stupendous, if it's been around this long, right? The result was less than stellar.

I bought a couple steaks as the first and final test of the product; it's hard to screw up a good steak, after all, so regardless of how hit-or-miss the product was, I'd still eat well. The George Foreman grill took a good 15 minutes to warm up, and went from "stone cold" to "nearly on fire" almost instantaneously after that. The steaks didn't cook evenly, the non-stick surface didn't, and cleaning the thing is a nightmare unto itself. I can see how a college kid would love this thing, and for that it's fantastic. As an actual kitchen appliance, it's a waste of forty dollars. Stick to the range-top and get better results.

Review: We stayed at the sandcastle resort/hotel in virginia beach for three days. Our experience was less than enjoyable. To start off when we arrived to check in, they could not find our reservation and the staff that was working there was extremely rude. They were confident that there was no reservation under our name so i went through my emails and showed them the one i received from them almost a month earlier. Finally after about 20 minutes we received our keys and headed to our room. When we got to our floor they were doing construction in our hallway and being very noisy. I went back to the front desk and requested that we be moved to another floor where there was no construction going on. they advised me they had no other rooms available but assured us that the construction would be done before 4pm. After going back to our room we found the room very dirty and run down. Paint was peeling from the ceiling and there were a lot of stains in the carpet. At this pint i decided not to make a big deal out of it until after we came back from dinner. We returned to the hotel just after 7pm and they were still doing construction on our floor. I wouldnt have minded the construction if it wasn't for the fact that they were very loud and drilling and cutting things with saws. I returned to the front desk again and requested to speak to a manager. After waiting for almost 15 minutes the manager finally arrived. We asked to be moved to a different room again and the manager finally agreed to move us to a suite for the same price we paid for our room. When we got to our room we found that is hasn't even been cleaned yet. The bed sheets were on the floor and there was trash everywhere. Apparently house keeping hasn't cleaned the room yet even though by now it was almost 8pm. At this point i was pretty upset and started to call surrounding hotels. we finally found another hotel that had a room available about a mile down the street. We went back to the front desk and spoke to the manager again. We requested a refund and the manager oked it. This was the worst experience ive ever had at any hotel, and to find out they still haven't refunded or 3 days to my credit card. I've been on the phone several times but have yet to hear back from the manager about the refund. I would not recommend this hotel to anyone and am very unhappy with the way we were treated.

Review:
I own a first-generation Apple iPad, and I can’t help but admit that I’m very disappointed. Although it is a very popular device, I feel that there are other devices which trump it when the features are compared.

Screen
The screen on the iPad has too low of a resolution. Other tablets which run android run at double the resolution of the first generation iPad’s screen, and it’s taken apple another two generations to remedy this problem. There is no haptic feedback, like you will find on competing products, making it difficult to navigate, and the on-screen keyboard is awful.

Software
Although there are many applications available for iOS, it lacks the customizability of Android. If you want to customize an iPad, you need to “jailbreak” it, using techniques not approved by Apple and not covered under your warranty. On the other hand, competing products are very customizable and allow you to write your own software, change the interface’s theme, and do all sorts of other neat tricks under the hood.

Hardware
The iPad is designed in a way which makes it very awkward to carry around and use. It doesn’t fit in a pocket, so you need a bag. You might as well just bring around a laptop computer. Because of its awkward size, I find myself using my mobile phone and my computer, and not really using the iPad as much as I thought I would when I first bought it.

Tablets, in general, are not as useful as you may think. The iPad tries to fill a void which doesn’t exist between desktop and mobile platforms. I would suggest looking into other options.
Truth vs. Deception Judgments: [T, T, T, T, T, T, T, T, T, T]

Review:
After having this phone for a period of approximately 20 months, I can accurately say that this phones glamour lost its luster a long, long, long time ago. In the beginning, I absolutely loved the phone. It was fast, vibrant and just an all-around amazing phone to handle. And then the cracks in the foundation started to show.
Within about a month of handling the phone, a slightly visible vertical line of dead pixels appeared down the center of the phone. It was hardly a disturbance because I could only really see it if I angled the phone a particular direction. Thus, naturally, I thought nothing of the phone. But, then, one day, a few months later, I awoke to approximately 15% of my screen covered in green-colored dead pixels. To say the least, I was mortified. There were (and still are) parts of my phone that I just don’t see any color whatsoever besides these horrid and circular dead pixels.
After adjusting to that problem, another problem cropped up: the battery life. Prior to this dead-pixel fiasco, the battery life on the phone seemed to last for days on end (and this was with extended use). But, then, again, one day, the battery life just seemed to not be able to hold a charge through out the day. It’s actually become so bad that the phone will not hold a charge overnight.
If I could, I would absolutely return the phone for a full refund. I will NOT be buying another HTC product and would not recommend this phone. Ever.

Review:
I bought the Weather Direct forecasting system by La Crosse Technologies because I wanted to have an indoor-outdoor thermometer along with something that could provide me updates in case of severe weather. The product was easy to install, with step-by-step instructions to guide me through the online setup process. One of the most important features to me was the ability to customize forecast and warning alerts for my area. I went to the La Crosse Technologies website, entered my ZIP code, and then it walked me through a long list of the various weather warnings, watches, and advisories and asked for my notification preferences. I could set it up to either not warn me at all, display a visual message only, or give both an audible and a visual message when the warning or advisory is issued for my area. Being in the Midwest where we can get just about any kind of weather, I appreciate getting notice of winter storm warnings in the wintertime and severe thunderstorm and tornado warnings in the summer.

The display unit doesn't take up a lot of room, but it is versatile in that it can stand up on a desk top like a picture frame or it can be hung on a wall. There were a variety of trim finishes to choose from, including a wood-grain look or a brushed nickel-appearing border so I could choose one to match my home's décor. The outside temperature display blended in perfectly with the siding on my house, so it is conveniently out of the way and doesn't look out of place. Plus, it's wireless, so I could put it where I wanted and not be tied down by how long the cord was or have to drill a hole through the wall to install it and connect it to the inside unit. The display is large and easy to read and provides all the key information I want at a glance including temperature, cloud cover, and even the sunrise and sunset times for my area. The La Crosse Technologies site also offered links to even more information online for a small monthly subscription, such as lightning strike maps and other hard-to-find data, so someone with a more serious interest in weather can have access to the same data used by meteorologists.

The forecast accuracy is as good or better than the weather service forecasts. A team of experienced meteorologists makes the forecasts from their headquarters in La Crosse, Wisconsin, so they are well experienced in all types of weather forecasting and for the Midwest in particular. There have been a number of days where the local TV station forecast was off by 10 degrees or more, but the Weather Direct forecast was right on! I'd recommend the Weather Direct station to anyone and am considering giving it as a gift for my brother and his family who live in Tornado Alley. The warning alert feature can be a life saver.
Truth vs. Deception Judgments: [F, F, T, T, T, T, T, T, T, T]

Review:
We stayed at the Cannery Pier Hotel a few months ago, and I have to say, we were sorely disappointed... After all the reviews we'd read online, all the beautiful pictures, we may just have gotten our hopes up too high, but it really wasn't what we were expecting.

Admittedly, it's a cute, kind of quaint little hotel. It looks beautiful, sitting out on an old pier over the Columbia River. Unfortunately, after seeing the condition of the pilings for the old piers immediately adjacent to the hotel, we had to hope that our room was on a high enough floor to stay above water if some kind of disaster struck.

We stayed in one of the One Bedroom Suites, and while it was a very nice room, I would have thought that for how much they charged it'd be a little bigger at least. It wasn't cramped, but definitely smaller than we expected. And as much as I hate to nitpick, the mattress on the bed felt cheap, with springs that turned into nothing but pressure points when you climbed into the bed.

The jetted tub was a nice touch, and was certainly cozy. But a window directly adjacent to the tub left it a little lacking in privacy, especially since there was another hotel that directly faced the corner our room was on, and it took us a bit of fiddling to figure out how to raise the privacy blinds (yes, it came *up* from the windowsill) in order to really be able to relax and not worry that someone in the hotel across the way had a pair of binoculars pointed our way.

While some people may enjoy the complimentary wine and lox they serve in the evenings, someone like me who has a severe seafood allergy has to avoid the whole lobby area during that time because coming into any contact with fish (of any kind) will end up sending me to the hospital.

Many people I've talked to simply raved about how "cool" it was that they had these old towncars to chauffeur you to your restaurant for dinner. Well, the one time we took a ride in the Buick they had there, we both developed such horrible headaches from the exhaust fumes from some kind of leak (seriously, don't they know that carbon monoxide is toxic???) that we had to ride the whole way there with the windows rolled down. In the summer that may not be such a bad thing, but in the winter, when it's raining? Thankfully our restaurant was very near the hotel, but by the time we got there, we were both freezing. We didn't take the towncar back, but rather called for a taxi. Imagine that, we were warm and dry and didn't get a headache!

Overall, it's a very cute hotel, and they're definitely trying, but there's definitely room for improvement.
Truth vs. Deception Judgments: [F, F, T, T, T, T, T, T, T, T]

Review:
The WWE All Stars Brawl stick is yet another in a line of controllers geared towards single games. I'm not really sure why companies keep making these things or why players are stupid enough to keep buying them. The first problem with it is that right on the top of the controller is an ugly graphic from the game. Now, you might like the game and think its fun. But will you want to stare at that same image in a year, in two years? Your use of the controller is likely to outlive your use of the game, and anyone who ever sees you play any fighting game is going to see that ugly graphic on the top.

Review:
This is an okay arcade-style stick for beginners, but I wasn't impressed with it. The product is half the price of the more typical Tournament Edition sticks, and it shows.

The buttons are as responsive as the TE stick's, or close thereto, but what really made it unimpressive for me was the actual 'stick' -- the ball-topped directional apparatus, I mean. If you're serious about using this stick, you're going to have to take that sucker out. It's very stiff, which made doing certain motions more effort than I'd personally like, and it has a very narrow window for registering diagonal inputs. Very often, this is the difference between getting an input that the game reads as crouch, stand, f.HP and getting the all-too-familiar quarter-circle-forward-punch Hadouken. Or worse, if you're playing a game that's heavily dependent on down-forward command normal attacks, like BlazBlue or Ultimate Marvel vs. Capcom 3, enjoy your dropped combos. Even really brainless things like Wesker's off-the-ground handgun shot are missable with the out-of-the-box quality of the joystick.

I wouldn't quite recommend this stick to a beginner unless they're desperate to switch to stick and don't have much of a budget, honestly; I take back what I said earlier. It'll build some bad hand habits that could just as easily be avoided by spending the eighty extra dollars, or buying from a competitor. I also tried some comparably priced Hori sticks, and while I was really missing the two extra buttons, the joystick itself felt a lot better.

I recently bought a Garmin ETrex GPS after reading a number of positive reviews about them. While I found a few positive things to say, I was left with the feeling that the reviews must have been written my Garmin employees or something.

I bought one to use as a backup on my sailboat and had problems from the beginning. The first time I turned it on it went into a "searching for satellites" mode ... permanently. I could not even shut it off, but had to remove the batteries to get it to power down. After 4 tries with the same result, it magically came to life. This is not a good way to start out when you are trusting your life to a gadget.


It has started up ok since that time, but after about 2 weeks of use it developed the very annoying habit of just shutting down every time it receives the tiniest bump. So now I have a maybe-trustworthy, maybe-not gps that has to be handled with kid gloves to keep working. The backlight stopped working after 1 month. Add to all that the fact that it chews through batteries at the rate of 2 every 45 minutes, and has a very difficult to read screen at any and all contrast settings, and you can see why I have to recommend to give this one a miss... or at least ask around for opinions from someone you trust who ACTUALLY OWNS one.
You might save yourself a couple of hundred dollars.

Review:
My husband and I were recently on a business trip to Seattle that coincided with his birthday; while he was working one day I made a spur-of-the-moment decision to celebrate by whisking him away to Victoria, British Columbia for the weekend. I booked a package deal which included ferry tickets, a champagne brunch, and two nights at the famed Fairmont Empress hotel.

I kept our hotel location a secret from my husband until we arrived, and I'm so glad I did! After we docked and cleared customs and emerged into the brisk air, we rounded a corner, and got our first look at the majestic old building. It honestly looked like a storybook castle with its pitched gables, gothic Victorian architecture and a fresh dusting of snow. We both audibly gasped.

Once inside, the front desk was busy with other guests from the ferry. My husband and I stood in line but took turns slipping away to poke around the warm, elegant lobby. It had fascinating objects like model steamships and faded photographs of royal and celebrity guests enjoying the hotel's various amenities over the years. We were therefore in a good mood when the customer in front of us threw what might politely be termed a tantrum. The young clerk handled the matter professionally and quickly. By the time she got to us she was incredibly apologetic. By the time we walked away from the desk, we not only had a seriously upgraded room (with a harbor view and free wi-fi) but a lovely written invitation to enjoy a complimentary birthday dessert in the Bengal Lounge! Amazing.

This hotel is wildly romantic in the snow; because of it we stayed largely inside, snuggled into impossibly comfortable sheets and pillows in our luxuriously appointed suite, sampling the abundance of delicious teas (the Empress is famous for their Afternoon Tea service) our room offered. We had breakfast in front of a roaring fire in the Empress Room, which featured heavy dark wood, intricate carvings and ornate candelabra hung amongst tapestries and paintings. We had delicious champagne and curry at night in the Bengal room, overseen by a full-sized tiger (skin, anyway).

This hotel was one of the few I've ever stayed in that I can actually say I was content to just spend time in; wandering various floors, exploring some fascinating history and relaxing in the refined yet comfortable ambiance.

A once in a lifetime stay!
Truth vs. Deception Judgments: [F, F, F, F, F, T, T, T, T, T, T, T, T, T, T, T, T, T, T, T]

Review:
I purchased the Garmin ETrex as a backup GPS unit for my sailboat. The main GPS unit in my boat is integrated in with other displays like navigation, wind, rudder angle an so forth. The problem with these is that they use too much power. 1.5 amps does not seem like much, but 24hours a day on an ocean crossing for 3 weeks really adds up and taxes the systems which generate power.

In any case, I started using the handheld ETrex one day, and never looked back. It is the pretty much only GPS I use on the boat these days because:

. one pair of AA batteries keep in running for about 20 hours
. I can easily carry it with me anywhere on the boat
. it has a data port that lets me connect it to the Cobra VHF
radio, where it displays lat/long using even less power
. it is rugged

I have sailed around most of the world using these, and have purchased three of them - no, they did not break, I dropped one overboard, and have a main and a backup version. They boot up quickly are as accurate as they say, and withstand a harsh marine environment. Salt air and regular soakings in passing rain showers have not effect whatsoever on it. The ETrex is easily worth the money in my opinion.

For whatever reason certain games are jumpy during the movie scenes, and another game was simply unplayable it was so jerky. I would suddenly have my character die in the midst of a battle I did not realize I had been in.

Sony also keeps updating the PS3, which is supposed to make the use of the system better. Not only can you refrain from downloading the update, but often the update just screws up another game. My basketball game went from smooth playing, one of the only ones that was, to being unable to start the first, second, third, or fourth time. It often took upwards of six restarts to get the game to play properly. When the next update finally fixed it I realized my save data had been corrupted and I lost much of the gameplay.

If I had not spent so much money on this system I would completely give up, but I did and no one will take a system and give me even half of what I paid for it. Next time Sony releases a system I might just go with Microsoft.

My stay at the Embassy Suites Hotel in Minneapolis, MN was NOT an enjoyable experience. The hotel bills itself as a fancy, upscale place to stay in the Twin Cities, but in my experience it is anything but.

I would definitely recommend this hotel to anyone who is on a budget, but would like to experience Hawaii nonetheless.

Review:
The MadCatz Brawlstick is a great investment for a beginning fighting game player, or someone looking for a stick that's easy to mod.

The buttons are godlike; they're almost as good as the Sanwa parts on the TE stick but obviously somehow cheaper, and that definitely helps the pocketbook. This is my third stick, and I bought it to mod, and I was happy to shell out only eighty this time rather than another one fifty for the TE.

On that note, the internal construction means that taking it apart to put in new sticks, new buttons, or -- if you're a tournament player -- disable turbo altogether, or rewire it so you can plink with Back/Select. Or take off the art, for that matter -- we love you, Triple H, but we don't want to touch your face every time we mash out a combo. (This voids the warranty, but I like my sticks to look sick.)

For a budget stick that works out of the box I can't really think of a better option, especially for an eight button stick, too. If you're a modder and are comfortable with switching PCBs the Tatsunoko stick, same company, might be an even better budget choice, but then you have to buy and swap PCBs, and that's a huge hassle. Out of the box, the Brawlstick is probably the best buy.

Review: When I decided that it was time for a long overdue vacation, I decided to do it somewhere small and laid back. That place was Charleston, SC. Since it had been a while since I had been on vacation, I did a lot of research beforehand. The choices had been between Savannah, GA and Charleston, SC. Since I live in GA, I figured that I could at least leave the state, and when comparing hotels, the pricing for Planters Inn (my ultimate destination) and its accommodations, (as displayed on its website) ended up winning me over. I guess what they say is right, you get what you pay for. Upon arriving to the hotel, it took forever to figure out the parking area and where to pull up to get assistance from the bellhop. There was no real designated area. I ended up having to call the hotel from my cell phone to have them send out someone for assistance. I figure it was just a minor inconvenience and brushed it off. Checking in at the front desk was fine, the young lady that greeted me was friendly enough and I was escorted to the elevator, which was in the process of having its system changed from an old fashion key entry to the key card swipe. I had several problems with this system on my stay, having to go get help from the front desk just to get back to my room several times. I'm an easy going person, by nature, so I didn't let this get to me, but it is still in the back of my mind that this is supposed to be a LUXURY hotel, these little things shouldn't be a problem. Once I make it to my room, on my first night, I figure it is time to settle in. It had been a relatively long drive, for one person, and I wanted to unwind in the big jacuzzi that their website promotes. First of all, finding a suitable temperature for the water was a pain. Warm would go to scorching with just a slight turn of the knob. Eventually I settled on mixing scorching with cold to get the desired temperature. Once in the tub, I realized the jacuzzi jets weren't as strong as I anticipated. They were quite weak actually. Another thing I brushed off because at that point I just didn't care. Once out, I decided to try this 4-star restaurant experience that they boast about and ordered the greasiest, slimiest little glob of foie gras I've ever seen or tasted. To this day, I'm still not sure if it was actually foie gras I was eating. Or attempted to eat. Thankfully I was able to order something else from one of the nearby restaurants. I would like to say that my trip got better over time, but it didn't. I tried the over-priced 4-star restaurant a couple of more times, but in the end ate elsewhere the majority of the trip. The location ended up being great for shopping, and I still say that the staff was pretty OK. I just don't think that I will be returning to the Planters Inn any time soon.

Review:
I went to Syracuse last winter to watch my team play in the Carrier Dome and chose this Econo Lodge because the prices were cheaper (because I found out later that it's in a pretty run-down part of town) and mainly cause most of the better hotels were already booked. I drove up there and arrived pretty late, so I was very tired and ready to get some sleep before the game the next day. After pulling into the small parking lot, I realized after driving around that all the "Free Parking" spaces were gone, so I had to drive down the street to a paid parking lot. Then, after carrying my luggage all the way to the hotel, I checked in and, in a sleepy haze, threw my stuff down in the room and went to sleep.

Not more than two hours later, I woke up from incredible itching on my arms and legs, so I quickly turned on the light and realized how awfully dirty my room was. Then I looked closer at my bed near the sheets and I literally could see many, if not hundreds, of tiny bedbugs crawling everywhere. I immediately ran to the desk, where no one was there of course, and after waiting for 30 minutes for someone to show up, I demanded another room. I then got the new room key, went up to it, and after opening the door, I saw that this new room was no more clean than the last. And yes, there were just as many bedbugs in this bed.

I grabbed my stuff and walked back to my car and slept there for the rest of the night. Needless to say, not only will I never visit this Econo Lodge again, I doubt I will ever even visit Syracuse again.

The Park Hotel Tokyo's service is excellent and the English-speaking staff are helpful and friendly. The rooms, though a bit small, as is common in Japanese hotels, are clean and have a stylish, modern appeal.

The lobby, which is on the 25th floor of the Shiodome Media Tower, has a beautiful view of the Tokyo Tower and there are often soft Jazz concerts in the evenings, giving the hotel a quiet, calm elegance. In the mornings, the lobby is bustling with patrons enjoying the excellent breakfast buffet. The buffet is not included in the room price, but I was fortunate enough to receive coupons on a couple of visits, and the food was excellent.

And when you're not relaxing in the lobby or enjoying your quiet room, the Park Hotel Tokyo is also within walking distance to several excellent restaurants and there is a Starbucks Coffee located in the basement of the adjacent building, along with a convenience store for late-night snacks or drinks.

The Shiodome area is primarily a business district, so unlike other popular Tokyo hotels, the Park Hotel Tokyo's surrounding areas are quiet on the weekends and evenings, though the hustle and bustle of the morning work rush can be daunting. That it's also a business district, however, means that it's a great hub for traveling, with many Tokyo Metro subway lines running through the area, as well the JR Shimbashi train station, leaving travelers a lot of options to get around.

Also, Shimbashi station is centrally located station, just a few stops from the main Tokyo station, Akihabara, the electronics district, and popular tourist destinations like Harajuku, Shinjuku, and Ueno.

Taking convenience, location, and atmosphere into location, the Park Hotel Tokyo has been and will likely remain my favorite hotel when visiting Tokyo.

I am very greatful to Amazon for this and this should serve a lesson to Sony on how to handle a defective product and how to treat loyal customers. Cheers to Amazon and a million jeers for Sony. Review:
I've stayed at the Park Hotel Tokyo and will probably never stay there again. For one, it's too far from everything. It's a ten minute walk to Shimbashi station (the nearest JR train station) and I almost got lost trying to find it. And to add to the inconvenience, when I tried to catch the train one morning, I got caught in the morning rush. Because it's a business district, I felt like a salmon swimming upstream just trying to get to the station!

Also, because it's a business district, there's not a lot to do nearby unless you walk a bit to get to Ginza, which is known to be one of the most expensive shopping district in the world. No thank you! There are a lot of restaurants in the area, but no shopping malls or arcades. I had to catch the train or subway to visit those kinds of places.

Then, the lobby of the hotel is on the 25th floor and there are almost no signs outside the hotel or near it to tell me where it is, so I had the hardest time finding it when I first arrived. And when I walked into the building, I thought I was in the wrong place because there are offices for the Kyodo News Agency from the 3rd floor (where I entered). Also, because it's on the 25th floor, it feels like I have to wait a lot to catch the elevators in the morning when I leave or the evening when I get back. And heaven forbid there's an emergency and I have to take the stairs down 25 floors!

I don't think I'll stay at the Park Hotel Tokyo again, and I'd recommend other travelers not to either, unless they enjoy getting lost. While it's certainly a nice hotel, it's too inconvenient and there are certainly cheaper places with more to do nearby.

I’ve always liked their historical ambience, and they’ve updated the décor in recent times which makes it an even more attractive place. The hotel is supposed to be haunted, and I would love to see a ghost, but to date, I have never had so much as one paranormal experience. The hotel is close to several of Galveston’s attractions that I like to visit. I come down to eat at nearby Pier 21 and have one of their shrimp poor boys, go shopping on the Strand and visit Moody gardens, which has a great saltwater aquarium and a wonderful rainforest pyramid, loaded with tropical birds and butterflies. If you want a loud, crazy place, then fly to Las Vegas, but if you need to relax and unwind, stay at the Hotel Galvez on Galveston Island.

Review: On my last vacation, I decided I wanted to go to a place that was quaint and quiet, but still had a suitable level of culture to partake in. This place turned out to be Charleston, SC. After doing research on hotels in the area, I decided on the Planters Inn on Market Street, a quite luxurious hotel for the area featuring a 4-star dining experience. Upon reaching the hotel the staff was friendly and greeted me warmly. Check-in was a breeze and soon I was off to my king room accommodations. Outside the room was a little round, iron-wrought table set for two overlooking the courtyard. The tall white columns were freshly washed and looked new and fresh plants were out. (The weather was a bit dreary the entire time, so I didn't get to enjoy that feature of the hotel very much.) Once inside with my luggage, the first thing I noticed was a card with my name on it and a teddy bear in the middle of my ginormous bed. The card welcomed me and the bear ultimately became a keepsake for my nephew. The bedroom was beautiful, and the bathroom was just as nice. The first thing I did was take a nice long, hot bath in the jacuzzi. It was the perfect way to unwind after my drive from Atlanta where I'd just barely fled some unseasonable snow. After the bath, I ordered the duck from the 4-star Peninsula Grill and a glass of champagne. It was my first vacation in almost a decade and I planned to live it up! My stay lasted a week, and all in all, each day was the a slightly different rendition of the first. Between sightseeing, visiting shops for gifts and keepsakes, and hitting up a few bead shops for my jewelry line on Etsy, I got to relax in some of the most luxurious accommodations I have ever had the pleasure of partaking in. The staff, from the front desk to the housekeepers, were all friendly and quick to answer any request. (Once I saw a bellman delivering chocolate covered strawberries that were not on the menu, he made sure I got some too!) It was a fabulous hotel and a place I plan to visit again in the future. Thanks Planters Inn!

Review: The Neutrogena Wave is a really great product that has given me nothing but positive results. I have VERY sensitive, oily, acne-prone skin and I used to have a monstrous amount of blackheads all over my nose and chin. It was gross. But, within a few weeks of using the Wave once or twice a week, my skin began to look MUCH cleaner, smoother, and even a little more radiant. The pads that come with the Wave are great and exfoliate my skin so well that I rarely have to use the Wave more than once a week, sometimes once every two weeks. Exfoliating makes it a lot easier for my acne medicine to sink in. I saw a huge improvement in the amount of blackheads on my face and my pores themselves were, and still are becoming cleaner and slowly tightening up. I love this product and would definitely recommend it to anyone who is having trouble with his or her skin.

Review:
I recently stayed at the Astor Crown Plaza in New Orleans for a work seminar. My seminar was being held in another hotel in the French Quarter, so I felt that it would be best for me to stay in the French Quarter as well. I got a somewhat reasonable price for the Astor and thought that it was in a good location when looking at a map of the area. I arrived with a coworker very late at night due to plane layovers and was extremely uncomfortable when getting out of my taxi. There were probably 7-10 random people standing outside the doors cursing and yelling. I had to walk through these people to get to the door and there was no doorman to make me feel more at ease with the random cursing people.

I went to check in and it went quick enough, however the woman helping me spoke only when spoken to and seemed very annoyed that we were checking in - like we had interrupted something. Just handed us our room keys and looked back at her computer.

The room was fine - no complaints about the cleanliness. However, it is IMPOSSIBLE to sleep! With all of the commotion on Bourbon street below, you must bring ear plugs if you even want to think about sleeping!

I was in need of some water and went down the hall to the vending area and tried to but a bottle and was unable to because it was sold out. I went back to my room assuming that it would be refilled at some point that night or the next morning. The next night, I tried again - no water. I then went to several other vending areas on other floors and no water there either. I went back to my room and called room service and did receive two bottles of water. I drank half of one and went to bed. The next day, I left the room for my work function and came back to see that housekeeping had taken my water!

All in all, the location of this hotel is fine, but customer service, and water, seem to be lacking quite a bit! I will be returning to the French Quarter but not to this hotel.

Review:
I purchased a Playstation 3 video game console a couple months ago to complete my collection of all three home consoles. My experience during these months was a complete waste of time. Don't get me wrong, it's an okay system, but it's just not for everyone.

I mostly play online games, so online features are what I look most for in a console. The Playstation Network falls short of what I expected. It's free, which is a plus, but I feel severely disconnected while using it. I have played Call of Duty on an Xbox 360 for years and had a great experience. I tried Call of Duty for the Playstation 3 and it just doesn't compare.

The Playstation 3 lacks cross game chat which allows you to communicate with your friends while playing a different game. I find this somewhat lazy of Sony not to include such a feature. I don't even hear very many people communicating on the same game. I think this is because the PS3 doesn't include a mic with the purchase because mine didn't have one and I had to buy it separately.

The PS3 does have a good single player lineup, but I haven't found any games that I can play with my son other than LittleBigPlanet. I think Sony needs to rethink their business model because they aren't catering to everyone. The Playstation 2 was a decent console with a large variety of games, but they seemed to have dropped the ball this time around.

I also did not like the controller. The back bumpers were okay, but the analog stick placement is really painful on my thumbs. Sony hasn't changed the controller much since the Playstation 1 days and it shows. I really wish I could use the Xbox 360 controller because it doesn't cause cramps on my hands.

I really don't recommend this console to people who like to play online. The service just isn't on par with the competition. If Sony would focus more on what people want then it wouldn't be so bad of a machine. I really hope the next Playstation is better because I respect Sony and I want them to step their game up.

I have owned a first-generation 32GB Apple iPad for the past year, and have found it to be a great device.

Screen
The iPad’s screen is large enough to enjoy movies, web pages, and photos on, but still small enough to carry around in one hand. The brightness of the screen is good, and the colors really pop out. The multi-touch technology works great, and makes it easy to use gestures to navigate the interface.

Software
Apple’s iOS is very stable, well-designed, and easy to use. There are an endless number of programs available for it, and generally the quality of the programs for iOS is better than for competing mobile operating systems, many of which I have also used. The best part of the software is simple the fact that it is extremely ergonomic in the way it works, and doesn’t require a lot of figuring out.

Hardware
The tablet is good-looking, the battery life is around ten hours, which is phenomenal, and the processor runs fast enough to handle anything thrown at it in a reasonable amount of time. The one button is easy to access, and the battery charges very quickly.

Overall, I’m very happy with my purchase, and have been able to use my iPad at home, at work, and to entertain my son on long trips. It’s a fantastic product.

Review:

For one, the battery life of the iPhone 4 is dramatically less than the 3GS, which never lasted more that a day with constant use either. I find that the battery drops to 50% after using the phone for just an hour, as opposed to the 3GS, which lasted at least twice that amount of time.

Another annoying aspect of the phone is that I tend to either accidentally hit mute or Facetime when I'm trying to call someone normally, which is frustrating because it either makes the other person think you've hung up or decreases call quality.
I find that downloading applications also eats up the battery life on this phone.

The camera, while clear and crisp in quality, tends to freeze up or crash when trying to take a picture and takes forever to load up. I've missed a great photo op many times because of this!

I could go on and on about why this phone is a disappointment, but I have hit my main points above. I wish I had stuck to my old phone - maybe not as modern, but it still did its job!

Review:
The engineering firm I work for recently spent some money and upgraded the cell phones they provide for us. We have been using BlackBerry products forever, but this time we got the choice of another BlackBerry or the iPhone4. I guess (though I don't like to admit it) the hype got to me or something, but anyway I picked the iPhone... to try something different, and to see what the fuss was about as much as anything.

BIG mistake! I really do not understand why anybody would ever choose this over a Blackberry, unless maybe it satisfies some psychological need or something. From a functional point of view I find the iPhone slow, cumbersome, and annoying. Logical work flow seems not to have entered the mind of the design engineers. "Oh look, I have a new message from Bill... I've been waiting all day to hear from him!"

blackberry - click on the notification, read the message from bill

iPhone - click on the notification, wait, slide my fingers around to get the message...oh wait, "retrieving message from server" ... wait, login, wait, slide fingers some more, wait, get first 12% of message from Bill, wait, 15%, wait, 23%, wait, 23%, wait 23%, wait, 24%, wait... ARGHH. Now repeat 27 times a day, and add fair at best wireless service with lots of dropped calls and inexplicable delays in message arrival (sometimes for hours).

to APPLE: I DO NOT THINK DOING FINGER GYMNASTICS ON A TOUCH SCREEN IS "COOL". I WANT EFFICIENT FLOW OF DATA! I didn't realize how important it was to me ('cause bb did a good enough job) until I got this POS.


Now I'm counting down the days until next year when I can unload this thing. Oh yeah, and did I mention the battery lasts seven minutes? well, maybe not that bad, but bad to the point of AGAIN INTERFERING WITH MY WORK by needing to be charged more than once per day.

Maybe they make sense if you feel some emotional connection to a giant company, or feel all warm and fuzzy about being an individualist (you and 30 million others), but if you need a tool for business stay far, far away.

Review:
Wow.

That is quite simply the first word that comes to mind when I think about the Cannery Pier Hotel. And the second. And even the third. My wife and I went to this hotel for our honeymoon, and spent an absolutely marvelous week here.

First and foremost, I have to say the staff here is simply incredible. Friendly, warm, and genuinely caring, they make you feel like you're visiting close friends or family rather than staying at a hotel.

Now, on to the hotel itself. We arrived early afternoon, a couple hours before check in time. The first surprise we had was that they had our room ready and allowed us to check in early. After a couple of hours on the road, this was very welcome indeed.

The room was absolutely beautiful. We stayed in the one bedroom suite, and the pictures simply do not do it justice. The wraparound deck provided a place to sit and watch the ships go by in the Columbia River (they even provided a complimentary set of binoculars!), or to just relax and watch the birds fly by. The jetted tub is big enough for two (and I'm a pretty tall guy) and was comfortable enough to never want to get out.

One of the treats at CPH is the wine hour. At 5:00, the staff puts out bagels, cream cheese, and lox, and then pours glasses of wine from different local vineyards for the guests. And again, this is complimentary!

If you want to go out for dinner, the staff will be happy to make reservations for you at any of a number of local restaurants, ranging from laid back pubs to upscale seafood restaurants. And when it's time to go to dinner, one of their staff will drive you to the restaurant in the hotel's 1939 Buick Towncar (I noticed from their website that they've added a 1938 Packard and a 1945 Caddilac). When you are done with dinner, the restaurant staff can simply call the hotel and the car will be by to pick you up. Again, this is a complimentary service. Just part of what makes CPH so special (we did give the driver a healthy tip every night we went out).

Finally, one of the things that actually has stuck with me since our honeymoon (and has us returning there every year for our anniversary, at least for one night) is this: About halfway through our stay there, my wife got sick. I went to the lobby, and asked the night clerk where the nearest drug store was. The next morning, when we came down for breakfast, the day clerk stopped us to ask how my wife was doing. The simple fact that they cared enough to make sure she was feeling better absolutely amazed us.

We look forward to spending many more anniversaries at this wonderful hotel.

Review:
I received the Weather Direct weather forecasting and temperature station for Christmas from a friend last year. While I've had a life-long interest in weather and was initially excited at receiving the gift, it was difficult to set up and didn't provide information as useful as I'd hoped. The station includes a display console, an antenna that plugs into a computer router and transmits the updated forecast, warning, and outside temperature information to the console, and the outside temperature sensor. The process to set up the unit took about 30 minutes and while it was not difficult from a technical standpoint, the antenna did not easily pick up the outside temperature sensor's data and was difficult to install.

Once operating, the unit was designed to display the current indoor and outdoor temperature, a 4-day forecast for my local area based on my ZIP code, and provide alerts for various weather watches and warnings that I had selected it to monitor. The outside temperature display worked for about six weeks and never did again afterward. Weather forecast updates came regularly, about four times per day, but the accuracy was questionable. The unit displayed both a graphical depiction of the weather (pictures of sun, clouds, rain, etc. on an LCD display) and the forecast high and low temperatures. It also scrolled the forecast at the bottom of the display console in text format. It seemed that the unit could only display a minimal variety of forecast scenarios and lacked detail such as precipitation chances or if a certain condition was only expected part of the day. The warning feature, which I thought could be a nice component especially for spring and summer severe weather, was slow to update and more often than not gave me alerts for events going on a county away from me instead of for my area. The incident that made me decide to stop using it was when it would only display a “Coastal Flood Warning” for weeks on end (I live in Minnesota, far away from any areas expected to be threatened by coastal flooding)!

As I found that online sources of information from the National Weather Service continued to have the level of detail and timeliness I wanted, and as the display console basically became just an attractive-looking indoor thermometer and nothing more, I decided to disconnect the unit, and I have not reinstalled it. Unfortunately it was past the unit's warranty period, so I am out of luck for a refund. Perhaps someone who is interested in just a basic forecast might like the product, but for the more advanced weather enthusiast the Weather Direct system from La Crosse Technologies is a disappointment.

Review:
Of all of the hotels a person stays at, when he or she hears the name “Hilton” you know to expect quality. Even on lower quality hotels Hilton lives up to the name that is brought by the chain. When I decided on a Hilton, in Chicago, right on Michigan Avenue I expected the best in service and quality. Apparently I was expecting too much.

We were checking in on a Saturday afternoon and told we could not check-in early. We let the valets take our cars, with our luggage, and decided to walk around until we could check-in. Our mistake. We really should have just gone and stood in line. When it came time to check in there were lines that nearly reached the door, even with every counter being attended to. It took us over an hour to check in to the hotel. I am not even sure why because when we checked in it was a matter of quickly processing and then giving us a key. Our check-in did not take longer than five minutes, and the staff was not all together friendly about it.

We went up to our room, which was one of the smallest rooms I've ever stayed in, and even in Chicago the price was bleeding someone dry. The bathroom was a mess of toilet paper just being slung about and the remote had no batteries. This was not a case of the hotel taking the batteries unless they are requested because when I told the employees about the mistake they asked me if I was sure there were no batteries.

We left for the day and returned late at night. I threw the deadbolt on the door, because we were in Chicago at night, and my friend and I went to order dinner from room service. As we were deciding on dinner someone tried to get into our room. A guest. Who had the right key. If the dead bolt had not been on the door the man would have walked in. I pushed the door further closed and told him we were calling management. Management came up, and hardly cared as they explained he was given the wrong key and escorted him away from our room. I asked if we could be changed to a different room and was told we could not because the hotel was full.

Now we slid something in front of the door as well once our dinner arrived to keep any other unwanted visitors away. It did not take long before there was another one. A maid tried to walk right into our room. She asked if we needed the room cleaned. Considering I had never bothered to complain about the bathroom I hardly saw a reason why at nine at night a maid would believe we needed the room cleaned. I once again was calling management, who never got back to me on that one.

Despite telling management of our problems with the hotel, and the staff, and the food (which was overcooked and they tried three times to charge us for something we didn't order) all we received upon check-out was an, “I'm sorry. Thank you for staying at Chicago Hilton.”

I will not be going back there, or to any Hilton if I can help it.
